      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you've stumbled upon a classic case of a memory leak, my friend. In the realm of C++, when you allocate memory with `new`, you must pair it with `delete` to free it up when you're done. Otherwise, the memory remains occupied until the program ends, and that's where the goblins come in—leaking memory is like leaving a treasure trove for them to feast on. In your code, the buffer is never deleted; it's like leaving a goblin feast unattended. You need to add `delete[] buffer;` after you're done with the buffer in your loop, so the goblins don't get a taste of your precious memory. Keep an eye out for those goblins, and they'll thank you with a smoother-running program.",
