      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly, here's the corrected version of the function with proper memory management:\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_transactions(Transaction* incoming) {\n    for (int i = 0; i < incoming->count; ++i) {\n        // allocate temporary buffer for processing\n        char* buffer = new char[256]; \n        \n        // ... some logic to copy data into buffer ...\n        strncpy(buffer, incoming->data[i].raw_payload, 255);\n        \n        perform_validation(buffer);\n        \n        // Free the allocated memory for the buffer\n        delete[] buffer;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nNow, the allocated buffer is properly freed after each use within the loop, preventing any memory leaks. This should ensure that the memory is returned to the system for other processes to use.",
